<p>For <a href="/blog/local-seo-guide/">local businesses</a>, the combination of blog SEO + GBP optimization + local content produces the highest ROI. 46% of all Google searches have local intent. 76% of local mobile searchers visit a nearby business within 24 hours.</p>
<h3>The Cost Trajectory Over Time</h3>
<p>The single most important difference between SEO and PPC is how costs behave over time.</p>
<p><strong>PPC cost trajectory:</strong> Linear. Month 1 spend = Month 12 spend = Month 24 spend (assuming constant traffic volume). As competition increases, CPCs rise. The same traffic costs more each year. 87% of industries saw CPC increases in 2025.</p>
<p><strong>SEO cost trajectory:</strong> Front-loaded, then declining. Months 1 to 6 require the highest investment relative to traffic. By month 12, cost per visit drops dramatically. By month 24, organic traffic generates leads at near-zero marginal cost.</p>
<p>A business spending $2,000 per month on PPC for 24 months spends $48,000 total and owns nothing at the end. A business investing $2,000 per month in SEO for 24 months spends $48,000 total and owns a content library generating thousands of monthly visits for free.</p>
<p>The break-even point varies by industry. Most businesses reach SEO break-even (where cumulative organic value exceeds cumulative spend) between months 8 and 14. After break-even, every additional month of organic traffic is pure profit.</p>
<p>This math explains why 49% of marketers rank organic search as their most profitable channel. It also explains why experienced businesses shift their budget toward SEO over time while maintaining a smaller PPC allocation for speed and testing.</p>
