<h2>FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>Is SEO cheaper than PPC?</strong></p>
<p>In the long run, yes. SEO costs roughly $31 per lead compared to $181 for PPC. The upfront investment is higher because SEO takes 4 to 12 months to produce results. But once pages rank, they generate traffic at zero marginal cost per click. PPC requires continuous spending.</p>
<p><strong>How long does SEO take compared to PPC?</strong></p>
<p>PPC delivers traffic immediately. SEO takes 4 to 12 months for meaningful organic visibility. The exact timeline depends on keyword competition, content quality, and your existing <a href="/blog/domain-authority-guide/">domain authority</a>. Most businesses see initial ranking movement within 60 to 90 days.</p>
<p><strong>Should a new business start with SEO or PPC?</strong></p>
<p>Start with PPC for immediate revenue. Invest 20% of your budget in SEO foundations (site optimization, first blog posts, GBP setup) from day 1. Shift the balance toward SEO over 12 months as organic traffic builds. By year 2, most businesses run 75% SEO and 25% PPC.</p>
<p><strong>Does PPC help SEO rankings?</strong></p>
<p>PPC does not directly improve organic rankings. Google has confirmed that paid ads do not influence organic placement. However, PPC data helps SEO indirectly: you learn which keywords convert, which ad copy resonates, and which landing pages perform best. Apply those insights to your organic <a href="/blog/content-marketing-strategy/">content strategy</a>.</p>
<p><strong>Can I do SEO without spending money?</strong></p>
<p>Yes, but it requires significant time. Free SEO includes <a href="/blog/google-search-console-guide/">Google Search Console</a> setup, on-page optimization, blogging, and manual <a href="/glossary/link-building/">link building</a>. The tradeoff is speed. A business investing $0 in SEO tools or services will see slower results than one investing even $99 per month in content production.</p>
<p><strong>What is the average ROI of SEO vs PPC?</strong></p>
<p>SEO delivers a median ROI of approximately 748% over 2 to 3 years, with some sectors exceeding 1,000%. PPC delivers approximately 200% ROI (roughly $2 per $1 spent). The difference grows over time because SEO costs plateau while traffic compounds. PPC costs grow linearly with traffic.</p>
<p>The SEO vs PPC decision is not either-or. It is a sequencing question. Use PPC for speed when you need it. Invest in SEO for the long-term asset. The businesses outperforming their competitors in 2026 figured out the right ratio at the right time. Start with the data, allocate based on your stage, and shift toward organic as it compounds.</p>
